@{
  Formats a TimeStamp value according to a Format string. The format
  string can contain date/time items consisting of @samp{%}, followed by
  the specifiers listed below. All characters outside of these items
  are copied to the result unmodified. The specifiers correspond to
  those of the C function strftime(), including POSIX.2 and glibc
  extensions and some more extensions. The extensions are also
  available on systems whose strftime() doesn't support them.

  The following modifiers may appear after the @samp{%}:

  @samp{_}  The item is left padded with spaces to the given or default
       width.

  @samp{-}  The item is not padded at all.

  @samp{0}  The item is left padded with zeros to the given or default
       width.

  @samp{/}  The item is right trimmed if it is longer than the given
       width.

  @samp{^}  The item is converted to upper case.

  @samp{~}  The item is converted to lower case.

  After zero or more of these flags, an optional width may be
  specified for padding and trimming. It must be given as a decimal
  number (not starting with @samp{0} since @samp{0} has a meaning of its own,
  see above).

  Afterwards, the following optional modifiers may follow. Their
  meaning is locale-dependent, and many systems and locales just
  ignore them.

  @samp{E}  Use the locale's alternate representation for date and time.
       In a Japanese locale, for example, @samp{%Ex} might yield a date
       format based on the Japanese Emperors' reigns.

  @samp{O}  Use the locale's alternate numeric symbols for numbers. This
       modifier applies only to numeric format specifiers.

  Finally, exactly one of the following specifiers must appear. The
  padding rules listed here are the defaults that can be overriden
  with the modifiers listed above.

  @samp{a}  The abbreviated weekday name according to the current locale.

  @samp{A}  The full weekday name according to the current locale.

  @samp{b}  The abbreviated month name according to the current locale.

  @samp{B}  The full month name according to the current locale.

  @samp{c}  The preferred date and time representation for the current
       locale.

  @samp{C}  The century of the year. This is equivalent to the greatest
       integer not greater than the year divided by 100.

  @samp{d}  The day of the month as a decimal number (@samp{01} .. @samp{31}).

  @samp{D}  The date using the format @samp{%m/%d/%y}. NOTE: Don't use this
       format if it can be avoided. Things like this caused Y2K
       bugs!

  @samp{e}  The day of the month like with @samp{%d}, but padded with blanks
       (@samp{ 1} .. @samp{31}).

  @samp{F}  The date using the format @samp{%Y-%m-%d}. This is the form
       specified in the ISO 8601 standard and is the preferred form
       for all uses.

  @samp{g}  The year corresponding to the ISO week number, but without
       the century (@samp{00} .. @samp{99}). This has the same format and
       value as @samp{y}, except that if the ISO week number (see @samp{V})
       belongs to the previous or next year, that year is used
       instead. NOTE: Don't use this format if it can be avoided.
       Things like this caused Y2K bugs!

  @samp{G}  The year corresponding to the ISO week number. This has the
       same format and value as @samp{Y}, except that if the ISO week
       number (see @samp{V}) belongs to the previous or next year, that
       year is used instead.

  @samp{h}  The abbreviated month name according to the current locale.
       This is the same as @samp{b}.

  @samp{H}  The hour as a decimal number, using a 24-hour clock
       (@samp{00} .. @samp{23}).

  @samp{I}  The hour as a decimal number, using a 12-hour clock
       (@samp{01} .. @samp{12}).

  @samp{j}  The day of the year as a decimal number (@samp{001} .. @samp{366}).

  @samp{k}  The hour as a decimal number, using a 24-hour clock like @samp{H},
       but padded with blanks (@samp{ 0} .. @samp{23}).

  @samp{l}  The hour as a decimal number, using a 12-hour clock like @samp{I},
       but padded with blanks (@samp{ 1} .. @samp{12}).

  @samp{m}  The month as a decimal number (@samp{01} .. @samp{12}).

  @samp{M}  The minute as a decimal number (@samp{00} .. @samp{59}).

  @samp{n}  A single newline character.

  @samp{p}  Either @samp{AM} or @samp{PM}, according to the given time value; or
       the corresponding strings for the current locale. Noon is
       treated as @samp{PM} and midnight as @samp{AM}.

  @samp{P}  Either @samp{am} or @samp{pm}, according to the given time value; or
       the corresponding strings for the current locale, printed in
       lowercase characters. Noon is treated as @samp{pm} and midnight as
       @samp{am}.

  @samp{Q}  The fractional part of the second. This format has special
       effects on the modifiers. The width, if given, determines the
       number of digits to output. Therefore, no actual clipping or
       trimming is done. However, if padding with spaces is
       specified, any trailing (i.e., left!) zeros are converted to
       spaces, and if "no padding" is specified, they are removed.
       The default is "padding with zeros", i.e. trailing zeros are
       left unchanged. The digits are cut when necessary without
       rounding (otherwise, the value would not be consistent with
       the seconds given by @samp{S}). Note that GPC's TimeStamp
       currently provides for microsecond resolution, so there are
       at most 6 valid digits (which is also the default width), any
       further digits will be 0 (but if TimeStamp will ever change,
       this format will be adjusted). However, the actual resolution
       provided by the operating system via GetTimeStamp etc. may be
       far lower (e.g., ~1/18s under Dos).

  @samp{r}  The complete time using the AM/PM format of the current
       locale.

  @samp{R}  The hour and minute in decimal numbers using the format
       @samp{%H:%M}.

  @samp{s}  The number of seconds since the epoch, i.e., since 1970-01-01
       00:00:00 UTC (Unix time). Leap seconds are not counted unless
       leap second support is available.

  @samp{S}  The seconds as a decimal number (@samp{00} .. @samp{60}).

  @samp{t}  A single tab character.

  @samp{T}  The time using decimal numbers using the format @samp{%H:%M:%S}.

  @samp{u}  The day of the week as a decimal number (@samp{1} .. @samp{7}), Monday
       being @samp{1}.

  @samp{U}  The week number of the current year as a decimal number
       (@samp{00} .. @samp{53}), starting with the first Sunday as the first
       day of the first week. Days preceding the first Sunday in the
       year are considered to be in week @samp{00}.

  @samp{V}  The ISO 8601:1988 week number as a decimal number
       (@samp{01} .. @samp{53}). ISO weeks start with Monday and end with
       Sunday. Week @samp{01} of a year is the first week which has the
       majority of its days in that year; this is equivalent to the
       week containing the year's first Thursday, and it is also
       equivalent to the week containing January 4. Week @samp{01} of a
       year can contain days from the previous year. The week before
       week @samp{01} of a year is the last week (@samp{52} or @samp{53}) of the
       previous year even if it contains days from the new year.

  @samp{w}  The day of the week as a decimal number (@samp{0} .. @samp{6}), Sunday
       being @samp{0}.

  @samp{W}  The week number of the current year as a decimal number
       (@samp{00} .. @samp{53}), starting with the first Monday as the first
       day of the first week. All days preceding the first Monday in
       the year are considered to be in week @samp{00}.

  @samp{x}  The preferred date representation for the current locale, but
       without the time.

  @samp{X}  The preferred time representation for the current locale, but
       with no date.

  @samp{y}  The year without a century as a decimal number
       (@samp{00} .. @samp{99}). This is equivalent to the year modulo 100.
       NOTE: Don't use this format if it can be avoided. Things like
       this caused Y2K bugs!

  @samp{Y}  The year as a decimal number, using the Gregorian calendar.
       Years before the year @samp{1} are numbered @samp{0}, @samp{-1}, and so on.

  @samp{z}  RFC 822/ISO 8601:1988 style numeric time zone (e.g., @samp{-0600}
       or @samp{+0100}), or nothing if no time zone is determinable.

  @samp{Z}  The time zone abbreviation (empty if the time zone can't be
       determined).

  @samp{%}  (i.e., an item @samp{%%}) A literal @samp{%} character.
@}
function  FormatTime (const Time : TimeStamp; const Format :
  String) : TString; asmname '_p_format_time';

